Introduction

Humans inhale oxygen and exhale carbon dioxide as a waste product. An excessive level of carbon dioxide in the air could lead to insufficient oxygen and imbalanced pH levels in blood. Additionally, CO2 is a greenhouse gas. An increase in CO2 level leads to the greenhouse effect where less heat can escape from the surface of the Earth, causing graduate warming of Earth’s climate system. This warming could have dramatic impacts on ecosystems in ways not foreseeable by humans, but ultimately could have a lasting impact on our global health. The goal of using these two datasets is to see if there is any correlation between the levels of carbon dioxide and global health over the years.

# read your datasets in here, e.g., with read_csv()
library(tidyverse)
library(gt)
CO2 <- read_csv("CO2_Emissions_1960-2018.csv")
health <- read_csv("country_health_indicators_v3.csv")

Wrangling

# your wrangling code
better_data <- data %>% rename(Country = `Country Name`, Emissions = `2018`) %>% 
    select(Country, Emissions, `Cardiovascular diseases (%)`:`Nutritional deficiencies (%)`)
better_data <- better_data %>% mutate(`Emissions>50` = case_when(Emissions >= 
    median(Emissions) ~ "True", Emissions < median(Emissions) ~ 
    "False"))

I renamed two column names and selected 10 variables of interest for the final dataset. Additionally, I generated a variable as a function of Emissions to give insight on Emissions relating to various diseases in later use.

# your wrangling code
table1 <- better_data %>% group_by(`Emissions>50`) %>% summarize_at(c(2:12), 
    .funs = list(mean = mean, sd = sd, min = min, max = max),

Grouping by Emissions>50, I calculated the mean, standard deviation, minimum, and maximum of the percent getting the selected 10 diseases. The result is reorganized in an easier-to-read table using the gt package. Interestingly, the spread of non-contagious diseases seems to have an increase when CO2 emission increases, but contagious diseases seem to fall down when CO2 emission increases. However, there are too many confounding factors to come to any conclusive findings.

Visualizing

# your plot 1
long <- better_data %>% pivot_longer(cols = 3:12, names_to = "Diseases", 
    values_to = "Percent", values_drop_na = T) %>% mutate(Diseases = str_remove_all(Diseases, 
    "[(/%)]"))

long %>% ggplot(aes(Emissions, Percent)) + geom_point(size = 0.3) + 
    labs(x = "Emissions (metric tons per capita)", y = "Percent of Disease", 
        title = "Risk of Dieases over CO2 Emissions") + geom_smooth(method = "lm", 
    aes(color = Diseases)) + theme(legend.position = "left") + 
    scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 40, 5)) + scale_x_log10()

This scatterplot depicts the relationship between Emissions and various diseases. As shown, about 50% of the diseases show a positive relationship with CO2 emissions while the other 50% show a negative relationship. Ones with a negative relationship are more likely to be infectious and transmittable diseases.

# your plot 2
long %>% ggplot(aes(x = Diseases, y = Percent, fill = `Emissions>50`)) + 
    geom_bar(stat = "summary", fun = mean, position = "dodge") + 
    geom_errorbar(stat = "summary", fun.data = mean_se, position = "dodge") + 
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 1, hjust = 1, 
        size = 7, face = "bold")) + labs(y = "Percent of Disease", 
    title = "Risk of Dieases") + scale_y_continuous(n.breaks = 4)

This grouped bar graph compares the mean percent of a disease in which emissions are greater and less than the median emissions. The resulting diagram shows a similar relationship as the last graph. About 50% of diseases are more likely to occur when the CO2 emissions is greater than the median emissions, and the other 50% are more likely to occur when the CO2 emissions is less than the median emissions.

# your plot 3
long %>% ggplot(aes(x = Diseases, y = Percent)) + geom_boxplot() + 
    geom_jitter(alpha = 0.6, aes(color = Diseases)) + facet_wrap(~`Emissions>50`) + 
    labs(title = "Distribution of Diseases Regards to Emissions", 
        x = "Diseases", y = "Percent of diseases") + theme(legend.text = element_text(size = 6)) + 
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 1, hjust = 1, 
        size = 5, face = "bold")) + scale_y_continuous(n.breaks = 7)

This grouped boxplot depicts the distribution of various diseases based on whether the emissions is greater than the median emissions. Most diseases have a similar spread regardless of whether the CO2 emissions is greater than the median emissions, except for common infection diseases, sexually transmitted diseases, and tropical diseases. All these diseases are infectious and transmittable. This finding is similar to results calculated using means as above.
